<p>
There are many other transformations and each one is considering a different space, 
which also means each one is more suitable for solving some particular types of DEs. This is a 
typical issue for most of algebraic approaches for solving ODEs or PDEs.</p>
</remark>
<theorem xml:id="thm-laplace-properties">
  <statement>
    <p>Suppose <m>f, f', \ldots, f^{(n-1)}</m> are continuous on <m>[0,\infty)</m>, <m>f^{(n)}</m> is piecewise 
      continuous on <m>[0,\infty),</m> and <m>f, f', \ldots, f^{(n-1)}, f^{(n)}</m> are of 
      exponential order with <m>c</m> as specified in <xref ref="def-exponential-order"/>. Then for <m>s\gt c,</m>
      <md>
        \mathscr{L}\left\{f^{(n)}(t)\right\}=s^nF(s)-s^{n-1}f(0)-s^{n-2}f'(0)-\cdots-f^{(n-1)}(0),
      </md>
      where <m>F(s)=\mathscr{L}\left\{f(t)\right\}.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

